# Bonneval Fine Wines — Complete brand design brief and wireframe

**Bonneval Fine Wines should position itself as the TWG Tea of Burgundy** — a brand built from scratch that feels like it has existed for centuries, operating at the intersection of French wine culture, Bulgarian provenance, and investment-grade exclusivity. The research across 15+ luxury benchmarks reveals a clear playbook: restrained visual elegance, heritage suggestion through adjacent history, allocation-driven scarcity, and WhatsApp-first concierge communication. What follows is the full strategic and design framework.

---

## The competitive landscape Bonneval enters

The fine wine merchant space in 2025–26 breaks into three tiers. At the top sit heritage institutions: **Berry Bros & Rudd** (est. 1698) with its Royal Warrant, Pentagram-designed identity, and BBX trading platform; **Corney & Barrow** (est. 1780), sole UK agent for DRC, Petrus, and Leflaive, with **75% of its portfolio exclusive**; and **Justerini & Brooks** (est. 1749), the largest domaine-bottled Burgundy importer with 55+ domaines. These merchants win on centuries of relationships and institutional gravitas.

The middle tier includes specialist boutiques like **Ripley Wines** (importing since 1983, transparent about how allocations work), **Flint Wines** (which absorbed Domaine Direct's 80+ producer relationships), **Goedhuis Waddesdon** (three-time IWC Burgundy Specialist winner), and **Haynes Hanson & Clark** (founded by Anthony Hanson MW). These win on deep personal relationships and curated access.

The investment-trading tier — **Liv-ex**, **Bordeaux Index**, **Cult Wines** — positions wine as a financial asset with Bloomberg-integrated indices and portfolio dashboards. Their visual language borrows from fintech: dark navy palettes, SVG data visualizations, and B2B SaaS patterns.

**Bonneval occupies white space in this landscape.** No merchant currently combines sole Burgundy import into Bulgaria, WhatsApp-first private dealing, and a luxury brand identity built from zero with TWG-level aspiration. The nearest parallel is the **Burgundy Wine Club** (Manchester), which uses WhatsApp and exclusivity language but lacks the visual sophistication and heritage framing Bonneval needs.

