## TWG Tea — the blueprint for building luxury from nothing

TWG Tea is the single most instructive benchmark. Founded in Singapore in 2007–08 with $10M, it broke even by 2012 and now generates **$90M+ in annual revenue** across 70+ boutiques in 23+ countries. The lessons are directly transferable:

**Heritage suggestion, not fabrication.** TWG's logo prominently displays "1837" — not the founding year, but when Singapore became a tea trading post. A Hong Kong judge noted this "led people to believe the company was established at that time." TWG never lies; it says it "celebrates the year 1837." Bonneval can anchor to Burgundy's deep timeline — the Cistercian monks who first mapped terroir in the 12th century, the Appellation d'Origine Contrôlée system established in 1936, or a specific year linked to the domaines it represents.

**Commodity-to-luxury elevation through packaging and ritual.** TWG sells tea at $40/100g by treating every tin as a collectible art object — seasonal designs, gold embossing, hand-sewn cotton tea bags. For Bonneval, the equivalent is treating every allocation offer as a curated event: printed brochures on heavy stock, embossed stationery, and presentation that makes a 6-bottle Burgundy case feel like receiving an artwork.

**Fashion-industry vocabulary.** TWG calls its teas "Haute Couture" collections and releases seasonal blends like runway drops. Bonneval should adopt similar language: "cuvée selections," "vintage campaigns," and "collection releases" that frame wine purchasing as a cultural moment, not a transaction.

**Never discount, never advertise.** TWG launched during the 2008 financial crisis and refused promotions while competitors slashed prices. Word-of-mouth, packaging-as-marketing, and placement in prestige contexts (Singapore Airlines first class, 5-star hotels) built the brand. Bonneval should follow the same discipline: no discounts, no mass advertising, no presence on generic wine marketplaces.

