## Typography direction — ceremony meets clarity

The type system pairs a display serif with an architectural sans-serif, following the BBR model (heritage in the serif, modernity in the sans) and TWG's approach (classical serif logo, clean sans body text).

**Display / Headings:** A high-contrast modern serif like **Cormorant Garamond** or **Playfair Display** — elegant, French in feel, with visible thick-thin stroke contrast that evokes engraved letterpress. Used for H1 headlines, the logo wordmark, and pull quotes. Generous letter-spacing (tracking +20–40) at display sizes to create breathing room.

**Body / UI:** A refined sans-serif like **Inter**, **Söhne**, or **Avenir** — clean, geometric, contemporary. Used for all body copy, navigation, buttons, and functional text. Weight variations (Light for large text, Regular for body, Medium for emphasis) create hierarchy without needing additional typefaces.

**Monospaced accent (optional):** For price displays, vintage years, and technical wine data, a monospaced typeface like **JetBrains Mono** or **IBM Plex Mono** at small sizes adds a subtle investment-platform feel — borrowing from Liv-ex's financial authority without going full fintech.

**Type hierarchy principles:**
- Headlines in the serif, always in sentence case (never all-caps), **always generous whitespace** around them
- Body text at 16–18px minimum, short paragraphs, maximum 65 characters per line
- Gold color reserved for the logo wordmark and critical accent text only
- Wine names always in the serif typeface, even within body text — treating each domaine name as a proper title

